tions and her own modern-character editions of the four works examined: Tang Yú zhi dao, Zigao, Rongchengshi, and Bao xun. In addition, she provides an introduction to Chu-script bamboo-slip manuscripts and the complex issues inherent in deciphering them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChinese languageyTo 600vTexts. 0aIdeals (Philosophy)xPolitical aspectszChinaxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aManuscripts, Chinese. 0aMerit (Ethics)xPolitical aspectszChinaxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aPolitical sciencezChinaxHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845779640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438457796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438457796/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles